        <tr>
          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              <BLOCKQUOTE class="ip-ubbcode-quote"><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-title">quote:</div><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-content"> Another reason to go 24-bit is that it offers better bass definition. Why? Low frequency sounds, like the picture below, have very long periods by definition, meaning that they change slowly compared to higher frequencies. At lower precision levels, the signal must be rounded up by a greater amount in order to match the closest value. By adding precision, the digital signal more smoothly approximates the signal's change over time, which we hear as cleaner, more precise low end.  </div></BLOCKQUOTE><BR><BR>This explanation does not make sense. Increased bit depth benefits all frequencies equally. Low frequencies, if anything, benefit less, because the human ear is much less sensitive to them.<BR><BR>Dan

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
