              <BLOCKQUOTE class="ip-ubbcode-quote"><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-title">quote:</div><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-content">Originally posted by redleader:<BR><BR><BLOCKQUOTE class="ip-ubbcode-quote"><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-title">quote:</div><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-content">Originally posted by Flawed:<BR>Given that, couldn't there be a method of representing analog sound digitally but without the stair steps?<BR> </div></BLOCKQUOTE><BR><BR>This is what PCM does.  There aren't really steps.  Theres a series of functions (sincs, which are a decaying sin wave) which are superimposed to create the output waveform.  As you suspect, a finite number of these can be combined to produce a (finite bandwidth) analog waveform exactly.<BR><BR> </div></BLOCKQUOTE><BR><BR>Not exactly.  PCM attempts to reproduce, but the point is PCM is only accurate at certain point in the time domain, and even then of limited accuracy due to how ADC works and bit depth limitations.  What he is describing is rebuilding an analog waveform from a formula so that all possible values are given.<BR><BR>While PCM approximates this, it is not perfect, which is why there is a difference between 44.1kHz and 96kHz.<BR><BR>          Seablade

              

              
              
